## Scaffolding workflow

This project was created by `scaffor execute go-hexagonal bootstrap`. The
next steps should use scaffor incremental commands, not manual coding.

**Required for any coding agent working on this project:**
Before writing Go code with Write/Edit tools, check `scaffor list` and
`scaffor doc <command>` to see if an incremental command covers what you
need. Manual coding is only appropriate for business logic inside generated
scaffolds, never as a replacement for the scaffolding itself.

Typical sequence for a new entity `Foo`:

```bash
scaffor execute go-hexagonal add_domain_entity       --set Entity=Foo ...
scaffor execute go-hexagonal add_repository_interface --set Entity=Foo ...
scaffor execute go-hexagonal add_repository_adapter  --set Entity=Foo ...
scaffor execute go-hexagonal add_usecase_interface   --set Entity=Foo ...
scaffor execute go-hexagonal add_app_service         --set Entity=Foo ...
scaffor execute go-hexagonal add_wire                --set Entity=Foo ...
scaffor execute go-hexagonal add_http_handler        --set Entity=Foo ...
scaffor execute go-hexagonal add_app_unit_test       --set Entity=Foo ...
```

For cross-context event consumption, `add_consumer_handler` is mandatory —
it generates both the handler and its boot-time wiring in one step.

## Architecture

This project follows hexagonal architecture. See `.go-arch-lint.yml` for layer dependency rules.

```
cmd/{{ .Context }}/                    — entry point (composition root)
internal/{{ .Context }}/
  config/                              — configuration loading
  domain/                              — entities, value objects, errors
    usecases/{entity}/                 — inbound port interfaces (Commands + Queries)
    repositories/{entity}/             — outbound port interfaces (persistence)
    publishers/{entity}/               — outbound port interfaces (events)
    services/                          — pure domain logic (no I/O)
  app/                                 — orchestration (implements usecases)
  inbound/
    http/{commands,queries,shared}/    — HTTP handlers
    grpc/{commands,queries}/           — gRPC handlers
    {protocol}/consumers/              — message queue consumers
  outbound/{adapter}/                  — concrete adapter implementations
pkg/{{ .Context }}/
  http/v1/                             — public HTTP types (requests, responses)
  events/v1/                           — public event types (consumed, emitted)
  grpc/                                — gRPC generated types + proto definitions
tests/e2e-api/                         — end-to-end tests
```

### Layer rules

| Layer | Can import |
|-------|-----------|
| `domain/` | nothing |
| `app/` | `domain/` |
| `inbound/` | `domain/`, `pkg/` |
| `outbound/` | `domain/` |
| `config/` | nothing |
| `init.go` (composition) | `domain/`, `app/`, `inbound/`, `outbound/`, `config/` |
| `cmd/` | `internal/{context}/`, `internal/{context}/config/` only |

### Config injection

Only the composition root (`init.go`) imports `config/`. App and outbound layers
receive their dependencies as constructor arguments — they never read config directly.
This keeps layers testable without config fixtures.

